A chlorine toxic endpoint of 1.9 miles resulted from atmospheric dispersion modeling for the Worst-Case Release Scenario, potentially affecting a residential population of 34,472. The program, RMP*Comp32 provided by the USEPA, performed the calculations. The USEPA program LandView6 calculated the population estimates.



The following conditions defined the Alternative Release Scenario 1 at the Edinburg Water Filtration Plant:



?    Failure of flexible connections (pigtails) connected to two, 1-ton containers resulting in the total release of 4,000 pounds of chlorine;



?    Release of the entire amount as a gas in 30 minutes;



?    Use of the one-hour average ERPG-2 as the toxic endpoint;



?    Consideration of the population residing within a full circle with a radius corresponding to the toxic endpoint distance; and



?    EPA mandated meteorological conditions, specifically a D atmospheric stability class, wind speed of 3 m/sec., and an air temperature of 77? F.



Atmospheric dispersion modeling for the Alternative Release Scenario resulted in a chlorine toxic endpoint distance of 0.2 miles and an estimated residential population potentially affected of 606.



The program RMP*Comp32, provided by the USEPA, performed the calculations. The USEPA program LandView6 calculated the population estimates.



